  1. What is the lift of the itemset: {CAPTAIN AMERICA, SPIDER-MAN}? What does the lift imply about the association of CAPTAIN AMERICA and SPIDER-MAN?
tList <- split(marvel$hero, marvel$comic)
trans <- as(tList, "transactions")

NT <- n_distinct(marvel$comic)

#apriori2df function
apriori2df <- function(x){
  if(class(x) == "itemsets"){
    out = data.frame(items=labels(x), x@quality, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  }
  else if(class(x) == "rules"){
    out = data.frame(
      lhs = labels(lhs(x)),
      rhs = labels(rhs(x)),
      x@quality, 
      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  }
  else stop("Only works with class of itemsets or rules")
  if(require(dplyr)) tbl_df(out) else out
}

Problem 2 (15 pts): Hero Clustering

Consider two binary vectors \(A \in \{0, 1\}^p\) and \(B \in \{0, 1\}^p\)

  • E.g. \(A=[0,1,1,1]\), \(B = [1,0,1,0]\) for \(p=4\).

The dissimilarity, or distance, between two binary vectors can often be created from the following three measures:

  • \(N_A\) represents the total number of 1’s in A. In example, \(N_A = 3\).
  • \(N_B\) represents the total number of 1’s in B. In example, \(N_B = 2\).
  • \(N_{AB}\) represents the total number of positions where where A and B both have a value of 1. In example, \(N_{AB} = 1\) (due to the 3rd position/element of the vectors)
  1. Write out the equations for cosine distance, Jaccard’s distance, and Squared Euclidean distance using \(N_{AB}, N_A, N_B\). Note: use 1-similarity to convert a similarity scores to a distance.

Cosine Distance: \[1-\frac{N_{AB}}{\sqrt{N_{A}}*\sqrt{N_{B}}}\]

Jaccard’s Distance: \[1-\frac{N_{AB}}{N_{A}+N_{B}-N_{AB}}\]

Squared Euclidian Distance:

\[ (N_A - N_{AB}) + (N_B - N_{AB}) \]

  1. The Marvel Heros INVISIBLE WOMAN and THING appeared in \(668\) comics together. Use the data from Problem 1 to calculate the three distances between INVISIBLE WOMAN and THING.
    • The vectors represent the presence or absence of the heros in each comic
#load libraries
library(dplyr)
library(questionr)

#create unique list of comics
comics <- data.frame(unique(marvel$comic))
comics <- rename.variable(comics, 'unique.marvel.comic.','comic')

#find comics with the two heroes in them
thing <- subset(marvel, hero == 'THING')
invisible <- subset(marvel, hero == 'INVISIBLE WOMAN')

#join to create 0,1 vectors for presence of hero in comic
thing <- left_join(comics,thing)
thing$hero <- ifelse(is.na(thing$hero), 0, 1)

invisible <- left_join(comics,invisible)
invisible$hero <- ifelse(is.na(invisible$hero),0,1)

thing <- c(thing$hero)
invisible <- c(invisible$hero)

Create \(N_{A}\), \(N_{B}\), and \(N_{AB}\) measures to use in calculations

na <- sum(thing)
nb <- sum(invisible)
nab <- sum(pmax(thing+invisible-1,0))

Cosine Distance:

1-nab/(sqrt(na)*sqrt(nb))
#> [1] 0.2408012

Jaccard’s Distance:

1- (nab)/(na+nb-nab)
#> [1] 0.3949275

Squared Euclidian Distance:

(na-nab) + (nb-nab)
#> [1] 436
  1. The dendrogram below is constructed by running hierarchical clustering using Jaccard’s Distance and Single Linkage on the 30 most frequent heros. Describe the first 3 merges. Who gets merged, at what (approximate) height are they merged, and how single linkage is used to calculate the height.

  1. Invisible Woman merged with Mr. Fantastic at height 0.28
  2. (Invisible Woman and Mr. Fantastic) merged with Human Torch at height 0.30
  3. (Invisible Woman and Mr. Fantastic and Human Torch) merged with Thing at height 0.36

Single linkage uses the smallest dissimilarity (Jaccard’s distance in this case) between pairs in the two sets in order to calculate the height.

  1. The dendrogram below is constructed by running hierarchical clustering using Cosine Distance and Complete Linkage on the 30 most frequent heros. How many clusters result if the dendrogram is cut at a height of 0.70?

What is the largest possible Cosine Distance between THOR and SCARLET WITCH?

If we cluster based on the dendrogram at a height of 0.70, there will be 11 clusters.

Since we are using complete linkage (the largest dissimilarity between pairs in two sets) and cosine distance, the largest possible distance between THOR and SCARLET WITCH is simply the height, which is at approximately 0.75.

This will be a contest. You will submit your 2017 density estimates at a set of evaluation grid points and I will evaluate your predictions using the predictive log-likelihood ratio (or information gain) score: \[ score = \sum_{i=1}^n \log \frac{\hat{f}(mile_i, time_i)}{p(mile_i, time_i)} \] where \(\hat{f}(m, t)\) is your prediction for \((mile=m, time=t)\), \(p(m, t)\) is my predictions, and the sum is over the \(n\) points in the 2017 test data. A positive score means that you did better than my predictions - you will receive a 4% bonus on your exam score!

  1. Describe the model you used. Make sure to mention why you chose your model, what the unknown parameters in your model are, and how those parameters were estimated. You may need to read the function documentation; I’m not looking for the mathematical details but do need to specify the method used.

I ran model-based clustering using finite Gaussian mixutre models (the Mclust function from the mclust package). The models are estimated by the EM algorithm, initalized by hierarchical model-based clustering, and chosen based on the BIC.

The ultimate model that this produced is a multivariate mixture with K = 4, where the clusters are diagonal of equal volume and shape, as this is where the BIC was the highest.

I chose to do model based clustering because I believe that there are multiple distributions of crashes throughout I-64 that may not be of equal shapes and sizes, so it would allow non-speherical clusters, different sizes, and different variances/densities, and model based clustering facilitates this fairly well.

The parameters that were estimated include the cluster means for the mile and time variables, the mixing probabiliites of the different clusters, and the variance-covariance matricies for each of the clusters.

Problem 4 (5 pts): Network Clustering

It was mentioned in class (or class notes) that community detection could be considered as a clustering of the nodes in a network. Spectral clustering is a clustering approach that uses the eigenvectors from the graph Laplacian as the features for clustering. In this exercise you will implement a version of spectral clustering. More specifically, the spectral clustering algorithm for \(K\) clusters is as follows:

  1. Find the eigenvectors associated with the \(K\) smallest, non-zero eigenvalues of the graph Laplacian \(L\).
  2. Run \(k\)-means clustering to find \(K\) clusters using the \(K\) eigenvectors as the features/variables.

Use the Laplacian \(L = D-A\), where \(D\) is the diagonal matrix with node degree along the diagonal and \(A\) is the (unweighted) adjacency matrix.

Hints: the R function eigen() finds the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix. There will be one \(0\) eigenvalue in this problem, but due to round-off error it will have a value on the order of \(10^{-16}\); do not include the eigenvector associated with this zero eigenvalue when running \(k\)-means.

  1. The UKfaculty network found in the igraphdata R package is a social network of university faculty. The graph can be loaded into R with the command data(UKfaculty, package='igraphdata'). Calculate the graph Laplacian using an undirected and unweighted version of the graph.
    • Show the code used to produce \(L\).
#load libraries
library(igraphdata)
library(igraph)

#load graph and convert it to a dataframe
# According to the package (https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/igraphdata/versions/1.0.1/topics/UKfaculty), this graph object is weighted and directed, so I convert it to a dataframe of edges and use that create an unweighted and undirected graph
data(UKfaculty, package='igraphdata')
UKframeEdges <- as_data_frame(UKfaculty, what = 'edges')
UKframeEdges <- UKframeEdges[c('to', 'from')]

#creating an unweighted and undirected graph
UKgraph <- graph_from_data_frame(UKframeEdges, directed = FALSE)


#checking to make sure it isn't weighted or directed
is.directed(UKgraph)
#> [1] FALSE
is.weighted(UKgraph)
#> [1] FALSE
#creating a laplacian matrix (https://igraph.org/r/doc/laplacian_matrix.html) using the laplacian matrix command - incldue weights = NA so the graph is unweighted
laplacian <- as.matrix(laplacian_matrix(UKgraph, normalized = FALSE, weights = NA))
  1. Implement spectral clustering of the UKfaculty network using \(K=1,2,\ldots, 9\).
    • Show your code.
    • Also plot the sum of squared errors (SSE) as a function of \(k\)
ev<- eigen(laplacian)$vectors

#drop the last eigenvector that is associated with the zero eigenvalue
ev <- ev[,1:80]

#run k-means clustering:
Kmax = 9
SSE = numeric(Kmax)                       # initiate SSE vector
for(k in 1:Kmax){
  km = kmeans(ev, centers=k, nstart=25)    # use 25 starts
  SSE[k] = km$tot.withinss                # get SSE
}

plot(SSE, xlab="K", las=1)

  1. Estimate \(K\). Explain why you chose that value of \(K\).

Normally, we would choose a value of K that is at a kink or elbow point, however, since this graph is linear, I am going to choose a point that is in the middle, so I choose the value of k = 4.

  1. Using your chosen value of \(K\), evaluate how well the resulting clustering can distinguish between the school affiliation of the nodes. Use the vertex attribute Group (in the UKfaculty graph) as the true label and calculate how many nodes would be misclassified by the clustering.
#run k-means clustering for spectral clustering
set.seed(112341)
km <- kmeans(ev, centers=4, nstart=50) # use K=4
#Evaluate the classification ability of K-means
table(true=V(UKfaculty)$Group, est=km$cluster)
#>     est

Using k = 4, 36 school affiliations are correctly predicted out of 81, with the rest being misclassified Largely, the clustering cannot distinguish well between the school affiliation of nodes. This is because the spectral clustering categorizes the vast majority of nodes into one cluster (75 out of the 81).
